<TITLE> Dutch want new referendum on EU treaty - poll </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 AMSTERDAM, May 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A majority of Dutch people want a referendum on a new European Union treaty, a poll showed on Monday, two years after the Netherlands rejected a draft constitution. Sixty-five percent of the 1,200 people polled on May 24 want a new referendum should there be a new treaty to modernise EU institutions, pollster Maurice de Hond said. Fifty-seven percent of the respondents agreed with Dutch Prime Minister Jan Peter Balkenende who said last week that national parliaments must have more say in vetting EU legislation if citizens are to accept a treaty. Asked whether they considered it good that Turkey was seeking to join the bloc, 65 percent of respondents said "no". Dutch and French voters rejected the draft constitution in 2005 referendums, plunging the European Union into a crisis of confidence from which it is just starting to recover. The Netherlands is one of six founder members of the bloc. EU member states disagree on how to revive the charter though diplomats said some consensus is emerging around a slimmed-down "mini treaty". The original treaty had aimed to streamline EU voting structures, create a more permanent presidency and a single foreign minist
